                                    &#160;</div></ulink></entry></row></tbody></tgroup></table><para>If you now open up your Home folder, by clicking on the plus sign, and select your newly created folder inside the Home folder,
            you will see button allows you to move a folder to someplace else "within your command" <graphic fileref="../../../resources/images/folder_go.png" align="center" valign="middle"/>&#160;.</para><para> Yet another button allows you to delete a folder that belongs to you, in this case the folder you have just created <graphic fileref="../../../resources/images/folder_delete.png" align="center" valign="middle"/>&#160;. </para><para> More complicated options are presented by the new button: Manage Folder Sharing <graphic fileref="../../../resources/images/user_edit.png" align="center" valign="middle"/>&#160;. The options afforded by this button are discussed separately, in the section on <ulink href="security-manager.xml">Sharing</ulink>. </para><para><graphic fileref="images/walk-through.12.png" align="center" valign="middle"/></para><para> The last button&#160;<graphic fileref="../../../resources/images/page_add.png" align="center" valign="middle"/>&#160;is in many ways the most important one: Create Stand-Alone Record (more about what "Stand-Alone" means below). 
            If you click this button, you
            will leave the Tamboti search interface and be taken to the Tamboti editor in which you can create a new record. 
            You will first be presented with a dialogue in which are are asked to choose which kind of record you wish to enter and which language is used in the resource (and which language
            you intend to use when cataloguing).</para><para> The search interface and the editor are linked in more ways than the Create Stand-Alone Record. If you are already in the editor or dialogue box now, you can click Cancel to
            return to the search interface. </para></chapter></book>